sentences: Mercy Dee Walton (born Mercy Davis Walton, August 30, 1915 – December 2, 1962) was an American jump blues pianist, singer and songwriter, whose compositions went from blues to R&B numbers.
He started playing piano at age 13 and learned his style from many of the ten-cent party house pianists that played out in the country on weekends.
In 1949, Walton made his first record for the small record label, Spire Records in Fresno.
Shortly after that, he had a national hit on Specialty Records with "One Room Country Shack", now considered a blues standard.
A half dozen tracks recorded for the Flair Records label in 1955, included "Come Back Maybellene," a sequel to Chuck Berry's then-current hit, "Maybellene".
In 1961, Arhoolie Records released an album recorded in Stockton, California entitled Mercy Dee.
Walton died of a cerebral hemorrhage in Murphys, California the following year.
"One Room Country Shack" / "My Woman Knows The Score" (Specialty) 1953
